    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>31 Cambridge Street, Hyde Park Sq. L—n</placeName>
                    <date>3/10 79.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Last night I received your exceedingly kind invitation to come down to your house.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> It would have been a very great honour and pleasure to me to have seen you, but hearing on my arrival here from Professor Hæckel<ref target="#foot.f2"/> that you were out of health and knowing how very precious your time is for science and humanity I did not want to disturb you for a moment and do not feel it right to come now and fatigue you by a visit. I believe that the work I am now engaged in—the organ of hearing of the vertebrates, from that of the fishes to that of man—will interest you. I have been unable to get on with it as far as I hoped; I came to London to get exotic batrachians and reptiles, but I have been very unsuccessful in this. When my work once will be ready, I hope to have the honour of sending it to you or perhaps, if you will allow it then, to bring it myself.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Retzius<ref target="#foot.f4"/> joins with me in kindest regards and thanks to M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Darwin.</p>
<p>I remain, dear Sir, | your most devoted and faithful | Gustaf Retzius</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12245A.xml">letter to Gustaf Retzius, 2 October 1879</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2048.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst Haeckel</ref> was in London in early September 1879 (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-12205.xml">letter from Ernst Haeckel, 30 August 1879</ref>); he visited CD on 5 and 6 September (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s copy of the first volume of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9720.xml">Retzius 1881–4</ref> is in the Darwin Library–Down; Retzius sent it by post (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13574B.xml">letter to Gustaf Retzius, 21 December 1881</ref>, <hi rend="italic">Calendar</hi> no. 13574b).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8298.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Anna Wilhelmina Hierta-Retzius</ref>.</note>
        </div>
    
